# Superhuman Review: Is the $25/Month Email Client Worth It?

[Superhuman](https://superhuman.com/) is the fastest email client on the market. It's built on a single philosophy: keyboard shortcuts are faster than mouse clicks. With over 100 keyboard shortcuts, AI-powered writing tools, and a streamlined interface designed for speed, Superhuman helps busy professionals process their inbox roughly twice as fast as Gmail or Outlook alone. The catch? It costs $25 to $30 per month, making it one of the priciest email solutions available. This review covers whether Superhuman's speed and AI features justify the premium cost, and who should actually buy it.

## What Superhuman Does

[Superhuman](https://superhuman.com/) is an AI-native email client that sits on top of your existing [Gmail](https://mail.google.com/) or [Outlook](https://outlook.live.com/) account. It doesn't replace your email provider, it supercharges it. The core promise: get through your email in half the time using keyboard shortcuts, AI assistance, and a clean interface stripped of distractions. Users consistently report saving 4 or more hours per week. The app is desktop-only (Mac and Windows), with a basic mobile app available on iOS and Android.

## Who Superhuman Is For

Superhuman is built for one person: the professional who lives in their inbox. Specifically, founders, executives, salespeople, and customer support teams who receive 50+ important emails per day and treat email as a critical part of their job or revenue generation. If you spend more than 2 to 3 hours daily in email and genuinely value your time, Superhuman's speed improvements translate to meaningful hours reclaimed. If you check email casually or handle fewer than 20 messages per day, you won't see enough return on the $25 to $30 monthly investment.

Superhuman also works well for teams that need to collaborate on shared inboxes, though the Business plan is required for CRM integrations and advanced AI features. Solo founders and sales professionals tend to be Superhuman's core users.

## Key Features

### Keyboard Shortcuts and Speed

Superhuman's foundation is keyboard-first design. The master shortcut is Cmd+K (Mac) or Ctrl+K (Windows), which opens the command palette and lets you instantly compose, archive, snooze, search, reply, or jump to any action without touching the mouse. The app includes over 100 shortcuts built in, and you can customize them. Early users report writing and processing emails roughly twice as fast as Gmail.

### Split Inbox

Instead of a single catch-all inbox, you can create custom inboxes for different email types using Split Inbox. Superhuman recommends creating a VIP inbox, a follow-up inbox, and a specific-project inbox. This transforms email from a overwhelming mass into organized buckets you can tackle one at a time. Combined with keyboard shortcuts, this is one of Superhuman's most powerful productivity features.

### Auto-Summarize

Every email conversation gets a one-line summary that updates as new messages arrive. Auto-Summarize appears at the top of each thread and helps you understand the context of long email chains instantly, without scrolling through 15 back-and-forths.

### Instant Reply

Using OpenAI's API technology, Instant Reply generates three draft responses for each incoming email. These drafts match your writing voice and tone, based on emails you've already sent. You review, edit if needed, and send. Early users report writing emails twice as fast. Instant Reply rolled out in October 2025 to Business plan customers.

### AI Writing Tools

Superhuman includes Write with AI (compose new emails faster), Rewrite in Your Voice (refine AI-generated text to match your tone), and Auto Drafts (automatically create follow-up responses). These tools are available on all plans, though Auto Drafts and some advanced AI features require the Business tier.

### Auto Labels and Organization

Superhuman automatically categorizes incoming mail using AI: things you need to respond to, things you're waiting on, meeting requests, newsletters, and marketing emails. You can create custom labels with simple AI prompts, then split your inbox by these labels to focus on one email type at a time.

### Ask AI

Ask natural-language questions like "where's the offsite" or "show me emails about budget," and Ask AI searches across your inbox, calendar, and connected documents (Business plan only). This replaces the need to remember sender names or guess keywords.

## Pricing Breakdown

[Superhuman](https://superhuman.com/plans) offers two main plans plus an enterprise option:

### Starter Plan
**$30/month** or **$300/year** (equivalent to $25/month with annual billing)

Includes:
- All keyboard shortcuts (100+)
- AI writing tools (Write with AI, Instant Reply, Rewrite in Your Voice)
- Auto-Summarize
- Split Inbox
- Auto Labels and Auto Archive
- Desktop and mobile apps

### Business Plan
**$40/month** or **$396/year** (equivalent to $33/month with annual billing)

Includes everything in Starter, plus:
- Ask AI (search inbox, calendar, and web)
- Auto Drafts
- CRM integrations (HubSpot, Salesforce, Pipedrive)
- Priority support
- Recent Opens Feed (see who opened your emails)
- Advanced AI features

For sales teams managing customer relationships, these CRM integrations work particularly well. See our [Freshsales review](/blog/freshsales-review) for a CRM option that pairs well with email tools.

### Enterprise
Contact sales@superhuman.com for custom pricing. Typically includes team collaboration features and volume discounts.

### Trial and Onboarding
Superhuman offers a 7-day free trial of the Starter plan. However, there's no self-serve signup. You'll need to request access and complete a mandatory onboarding call before you can start using the service. This onboarding is brief but non-negotiable, which some users find inconvenient.

### Hidden Costs
There are no hidden costs or surprise charges. Annual billing saves you 15 to 20 percent compared to monthly. There's no free plan and no freemium tier, so you're either paying or you're not using Superhuman.

## Strengths: Why Superhuman Users Love It

### 1. Genuinely Faster Email Processing

This is not marketing hype. Users consistently report finishing their email 30 to 50 percent faster after adopting Superhuman's keyboard-first workflow. If you process 100+ emails per day, this translates to real time saved.

### 2. Keyboard-First Design Actually Works

Unlike tools that bolt shortcuts onto a GUI, Superhuman is built from the ground up for keyboard efficiency. Once you learn the shortcuts, you never want to go back to mouse-clicking through email.

### 3. Strong AI Features

Auto-Summarize works quietly in the background and saves you from re-reading long threads. Instant Reply is one of the best AI email drafting tools available, and it actually matches your writing style rather than sounding generic. The AI features feel refined and useful, not like gimmicks. For additional AI writing support beyond email, check out our [Grammarly review](/blog/grammarly-review).

### 4. Split Inbox Prevents Email Overload

Creating custom inboxes for VIPs, follow-ups, and projects transforms how you think about email triage. You can tackle one type of email at a time instead of treating your inbox as a fire hose. This organization pairs well with newsletter platforms like [Beehiiv](/blog/beehiiv-review) if you're managing customer communications and email marketing.

### 5. Works with Gmail and Outlook

Superhuman supports both [Gmail](https://mail.google.com/) and [Outlook](https://outlook.live.com/), including [Google Workspace](https://workspace.google.com/) and Microsoft 365 business accounts. You don't need to switch email providers.

### 6. Minimal and Distraction-Free Interface

Superhuman strips away the clutter that slows down Gmail and Outlook. There are no ads, no unnecessary UI elements, and no notifications begging you to click. The interface is clean and focused on getting you through email fast.

### 7. Strong Community and Learning Curve

Superhuman has a small but dedicated user base. There are cheat sheets, video guides, and a supportive community on Reddit and Discord. Once you commit to learning the shortcuts, adoption is fast.

## Weaknesses: Why Superhuman Isn't for Everyone

### 1. Expensive for What It Is

$25 to $30 per month is a significant premium for an email client. [Gmail](https://mail.google.com/) is free. [Outlook](https://outlook.live.com/) is free or included with Microsoft 365. Superhuman's price tag is 10 to 30 times higher. You need to be very committed to your email workflow for this to make sense.

### 2. Steep Learning Curve

Superhuman demands commitment. If you don't embrace the keyboard-first methodology, you're paying $30/month for a slightly prettier version of Gmail. You need to spend at least a few hours learning the shortcuts and building the habit. Casual email users will see no benefit.

### 3. Limited Email Provider Support

Superhuman only works with [Gmail](https://mail.google.com/) and [Outlook](https://outlook.live.com/). If you use a corporate email system, a privacy-focused provider like [Proton Mail](https://protonmail.com/), or any other service, you cannot use Superhuman at all.

### 4. Limited Integrations

While the Business plan adds connectors for [HubSpot](https://www.hubspot.com/), [Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com/), and [Pipedrive](https://www.pipedrive.com/), Superhuman's integration ecosystem is small. There's no native support for [Slack](https://slack.com/), [Trello](https://trello.com/), [Asana](https://asana.com/), or most other productivity tools. If your workflow relies on cross-app automation, Superhuman won't fit well.

### 5. No Free Trial Alternative

Superhuman doesn't offer a traditional free trial signup. You have to request access and schedule an onboarding call, which is a friction point. Some users also report that Superhuman's 7-day trial window feels short for learning 100+ keyboard shortcuts.

### 6. Missing Basic Features

Surprisingly, Superhuman lacks some standard features you'd expect: you can't clear the trash from within the app (you have to go to Gmail), bulk-marking emails as read doesn't work consistently, and some highly requested features remain on the roadmap months or years after they're requested. This suggests the Superhuman team is selective about scope, which can frustrate power users.

### 7. Mobile App Is Weak

The iPhone and Android apps are bare-bones. You lose most of Superhuman's keyboard shortcuts and speed advantages on mobile. If you rely on email management from your phone, the mobile experience will disappoint you.

## Alternatives to Superhuman

If Superhuman's price or limitations don't fit, here are solid alternatives:

### Gmail (Free)
[Gmail](https://mail.google.com/) is still one of the best free email clients available. It has strong search, automatic categorization, and basic keyboard shortcuts. If you're trying to save money, Gmail's features are surprisingly good.

### Outlook (Free or Included)
[Outlook](https://outlook.live.com/) works well if you're already on Microsoft 365. It supports email, calendar, and tasks in one interface. The keyboard shortcuts and features aren't as extensive as Superhuman's, but it's included in your Microsoft subscription.

### Spark Mail (Free + Premium)
[Spark](https://sparkmailapp.com/) is a free email client with a premium tier ($7.99/month). It has a beautiful Smart Inbox that sorts mail into Personal, Notifications, and Newsletters categories. Spark is significantly cheaper than Superhuman and includes team collaboration features. The main trade-off is that Spark lacks the keyboard-first design and some of Superhuman's advanced AI features.

### Shortwave (Free + Premium)
[Shortwave](https://shortwave.com/) is an AI-native email client built specifically for Gmail. It includes AI-powered search, thread summaries, auto-labels, and a writing assistant. Shortwave has a free tier and is cheaper than Superhuman. If you only use Gmail, Shortwave is an excellent alternative.

### Missive (Free + Premium)
[Missive](https://missiveapp.com/) is positioned as a team email and messaging platform. It costs half what Superhuman does, supports more email providers, and includes shared inboxes and internal chat threads. If you're managing customer emails or working with a team, Missive is a better fit than Superhuman.

### HEY (Paid)
[HEY](https://hey.com/) is a completely redesigned email service (not a client). It blocks unknown senders by default, organizes mail into categories like The Screener and HEY Feed, and costs $99/year. HEY forces a privacy-first mindset and works best if you're willing to switch email addresses.

### Thunderbird (Free)
[Thunderbird](https://www.thunderbird.net/) is a free, open-source email client. It's lightweight, works with any email provider, and includes calendar and task management. Thunderbird lacks modern AI features, but it's completely free and respects your privacy.

## FAQ: People Also Ask

### Is Superhuman worth $30 a month?

Yes, if you spend 2+ hours per day in email and treat email as critical to your job or revenue. Founders, executives, and salespeople with high email volume consistently report that Superhuman pays for itself through time saved. If you check email casually or handle fewer than 20 messages per day, the cost won't make sense for you.

### How much faster is Superhuman than Gmail?

Users report processing email about 2x faster with Superhuman compared to Gmail. This comes from eliminating mouse clicks via keyboard shortcuts, auto-summarize reducing re-reading time, and the streamlined interface removing distractions. The exact improvement depends on how well you adopt the keyboard shortcuts and the structure of your email workflow.

### Can you use Superhuman with corporate email?

Superhuman only works with [Gmail](https://mail.google.com/) and [Outlook](https://outlook.live.com/). If you use Microsoft 365 business email or Google Workspace, you're fine. If your company uses a proprietary or on-premises email system, you cannot use Superhuman.

### Does Superhuman have a free tier?

No. Superhuman has a 7-day trial (which requires scheduling an onboarding call), but there's no permanent free plan. You either pay $25 to $30 per month or you don't use it.

### What's the difference between Starter and Business plans?

The Starter plan ($25 to $30/month) includes keyboard shortcuts, AI writing tools, auto-summarize, and split inbox. The Business plan ($33 to $40/month) adds Ask AI, Auto Drafts, CRM integrations (HubSpot, Salesforce, Pipedrive), and priority support. If you're a solo user, Starter is usually enough. If you're managing sales pipeline or need to automate email workflows, Business is worth the extra $5 to $10 per month.

### Is Superhuman owned by Grammarly now?

Yes. In July 2025, [Grammarly](https://www.grammarly.com/) announced the acquisition of Superhuman. In October 2025, Grammarly rebranded its parent company as Superhuman, uniting Grammarly, Coda, and Superhuman Mail under one corporate umbrella. The Superhuman Mail product (the email client) hasn't changed, but it's now part of a broader Superhuman suite that includes writing assistance, workspace collaboration, and a new AI assistant called Superhuman Go.

### How long does it take to learn Superhuman?

Most users get comfortable with core shortcuts (compose, archive, snooze, search, reply) within 1 to 2 hours. Mastering all 100+ shortcuts takes several weeks of regular use. Superhuman provides cheat sheets and video guides to speed up the learning curve. The onboarding call includes a 30-minute walkthrough, which helps beginners get started faster.

### Can you use Superhuman on mobile?

Yes, Superhuman has iOS and Android apps, but they're significantly less powerful than the desktop version. Mobile apps don't include keyboard shortcuts and lack some desktop features. If you manage most of your email from a phone, Superhuman isn't the right choice. If you primarily use desktop and check email occasionally on mobile, the mobile app will be fine.

### What if I don't commit to the keyboard-first workflow?

Then Superhuman isn't worth $30/month. You'll be paying for a premium client but only using 20 percent of its capabilities. Superhuman is explicitly designed for keyboard-first users. If you prefer mouse-based navigation, Superhuman will frustrate you.

## Verdict: Should You Buy Superhuman?

**Buy Superhuman if:**
- You spend 2+ hours per day in email
- You receive 50+ important messages per day
- You're a founder, executive, salesperson, or customer support professional
- You're willing to invest a few hours learning keyboard shortcuts
- You use Gmail or Outlook as your email provider
- You value your time highly and can justify $25 to $30/month as a productivity investment

**Skip Superhuman if:**
- You check email casually (fewer than 20 messages per day)
- You're not willing to commit to learning keyboard shortcuts
- You use an email provider other than Gmail or Outlook
- You need a free or very cheap email client
- You rely heavily on mobile email management
- You need deep integrations with tools like Slack, Asana, or Trello

**The Bottom Line:**

Superhuman is the fastest email client available, and the AI features (Instant Reply, Auto-Summarize, Ask AI) are genuinely useful for high-volume email users. The price tag is steep, and you absolutely must embrace the keyboard-first methodology to see ROI. If you're a founder or executive who lives in your inbox, Superhuman will save you 4+ hours per week and is worth every dollar. If you're casual about email, save your money and use Gmail or Spark. Superhuman's value is directly proportional to your email volume and commitment to the tool.

The 2025 Grammarly acquisition adds long-term credibility (the tool isn't going anywhere), and new features like Superhuman Go promise future integration across your entire workflow. For now, Superhuman is a specialist tool that solves one problem extremely well: making you faster at email. It's not for everyone, but for the right user, it's indispensable.

## Get Started with Superhuman

Ready to try Superhuman? Visit [superhuman.com](https://superhuman.com/) to request access. You'll get a 7-day trial after completing the onboarding call. No credit card is required for the trial.

